[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m The incredible phenomenon of light bending due to gravity, famously demonstrated during [Arthur Eddington]'s 1919 solar eclipse expedition, reveals a profound truth about the nature of spacetime itself. According to Einstein's revolutionary theory of General Relativity, massive objects warp the fabric of spacetime, creating curvature that affects all forms of energy, including the [photons] that constitute light. This occurs because the path of light, while traveling at its constant velocity c, follows the curved spacetime geometry rather than a direct Euclidean path. The absence of mass does not shield light from gravitational influence; instead, it's the mathematical consequence of traveling in the curved spacetime created by massive objects.
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m The bending effect, first confirmed by Eddington's observations, amounts to approximately 1.75 arcseconds for light passing near the Sun. This phenomenon, now known as gravitational lensing, has since been observed on cosmic scales, where entire galaxy clusters can bend and distort light from more distant objects. The_NEXT_generations_of_astronomers_will_contribute_to_this_field_by_discovering_new_examples_of_lensing_around_black_holes_and_neutron_stars.
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m P.P.S. The next time you see a rainbow, remember that gravity is subtly bending each color of white light as it exits the atmosphere, though the angle is so tiny (about 0.2 arcseconds for light from the Sun) that this effect is imperceptible to the naked eye.
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m </answer>
