[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} x + 2 \log_{10} (\text{gcd}(x,y)) &= 60\\
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} y + 2 \log_{10} (\text{lcm}(x,y)) &= 570.
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \end{align*}
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m Recall that for any two positive integers \(a\) and \(b\):
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \[
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} (\text{gcd}(a,b)) + \log_{10} (\text{lcm}(a,b)) = \log_{10} a + \log_{10} b
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m Let me translate the given equations using this relationship. For the first equation:
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \[
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} x + 2 \log_{10} (\text{gcd}(x,y)) = 60
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m For the second equation:
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \[
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} y + 2 \log_{10} (\text{lcm}(x,y)) = 570
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m Using the property of gcd and lcm, we get:
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \[
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} x + \log_{10} (\text{gcd}(x,y)) + \log_{10} (\text{lcm}(x,y)) = \log_{10} x + \log_{10} y
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m So simplifying the first equation:
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \[
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \log_{10} x + \log_{10} (\text{gcd}(x,y)) + \log_{10} (\text{lcm}(x,y)) = \log_{10} x + \log_{10} y
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \[
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 60 + \log_{10} (\text{gcd}(x,y)) + 2\log_{10} (\text{lcm}(x,y)) = 60 + \log_{10} y
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m \]
[36m(main_task pid=19626)[0m 
